r addresses a central theoretical question: How can environmentally oriented, spiritually motivated individuals and movements be understood as religious when many of them reject religious and supernatural worldviews? The "dark" of the title further expands this idea by emphasizing the depth of believers' passion and also suggesting a potential shadow side: besides uplifting and inspiring, such religion might mislead, deceive, or in some cases precipitate violence. This book provides a fascinating global tour of the green religious phenomenon, enabling readers to evaluate its worldwide emergence and to assess its role in a critically important religious revolution.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aNature worship. 0aNaturexReligious aspects. 7aRELIGION / Comparative Religion.2bisacsh  adark green religion.  aeco psychology.  aenvironmentalism.  aglobalization.  agreen religion phenomenon.  agreen religions.  ainnovative.  alifestyle focused bioregionalists.  anature.  anew age.  anew religions.  anon traditional religions.  anorth america.  apassion.  aplanetary future.  aradical environmental activism.  aradical environmentalism.  areligion.  areligious revolution.  areligious studies.  asacred.  aspiritual practices.  aspirituality.  asupernatural.  asurfers.  aterrapolitan earth religion.  aviolence.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052023775940uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052094445940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520944459423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520944459/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZD